  "prompt": "When considering co-founders, I picked the designer and the genius (I'm the voice).  Lately I've begun studying what investors look for in a startup, and see that we may raise red flags by not having a programmer as a founder.  Is a technical founder something we have to have?",
  "response": "Having a technical founder is highly beneficial but not always mandatory. Here are some key perspectives:\n\nWhy a technical founder matters:\n- Reduces development costs\n- Demonstrates ability to build product in-house\n- Provides credibility with tech investors\n- Can pivot and iterate quickly\n- Understands technical feasibility of vision\n\nAlternatives if you lack a technical founder:\n- Bring on a technical co-founder\n- Have a strong technical advisor on board\n- Budget for outsourced/contracted development\n- Use no-code/low-code platforms initially\n- Demonstrate technical competence through detailed product roadmap\n\nInvestor perspective:\n- Most prefer at least one founder who can technically execute\n- Technical founders signal lower risk and higher potential\n- Non-technical teams can succeed but face higher scrutiny\n\nRecommendations:\n1. Actively network to find potential technical co-founder\n2. Build robust technical advisory board\n3. Demonstrate deep technical understanding of your product\n4. Show clear development strategy\n5. Have detailed technical specifications\n\nYour current team sounds strong in design and strategy. Focus on complementing those skills with technical expertise.\n\nWould you like to explore specific strategies for finding a technical co-founder?",
